1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,950
In this video, we're going to look at how to scale and transform our axis.

2
00:00:06,950 --> 00:00:09,015
We're going to start as always,

3
00:00:09,015 --> 00:00:13,845
by importing the necessary libraries and our dataset.

4
00:00:13,845 --> 00:00:19,200
In this exercise, we'll be focused on the diamonds dataset.

5
00:00:19,200 --> 00:00:23,385
We're going to look specifically at diamond price.

6
00:00:23,385 --> 00:00:27,585
This variable is quite skewed.

7
00:00:27,585 --> 00:00:32,570
One thing we might want to do is we might consider that

8
00:00:32,570 --> 00:00:39,515
this price is logarithmically distributed and not distributed in a base 10 system.

9
00:00:39,515 --> 00:00:43,925
So we're going to transform the axis and take a look.

10
00:00:43,925 --> 00:00:48,670
To do this, we're going to be using the matplotlib xscale function.

11
00:00:48,670 --> 00:00:53,445
This takes a string such as log or semi-log.

12
00:00:53,445 --> 00:00:57,170
In this case, for our histogram,

13
00:00:57,170 --> 00:01:04,895
I am going to collect the axis object and then use the same function set_xscale.

14
00:01:04,895 --> 00:01:08,725
Notice, this plot looks pretty weird.

15
00:01:08,725 --> 00:01:13,835
The x limits themselves are not changed, but they're scaled.

16
00:01:13,835 --> 00:01:16,625
In order to get a more interpretable plot,

17
00:01:16,625 --> 00:01:19,370
we're going to need to modify the bin boundaries

18
00:01:19,370 --> 00:01:22,715
and generate more informative access texts.

19
00:01:22,715 --> 00:01:25,970
Let's start by looking at the bin boundaries.

20
00:01:25,970 --> 00:01:29,930
If we look at the price and do a describe on that column,

21
00:01:29,930 --> 00:01:34,210
we will see that the minimum price is a little over $300.

22
00:01:34,210 --> 00:01:38,685
The maximum price is almost $20,000.

23
00:01:38,685 --> 00:01:43,370
If we're going to assume that price is logarithmically distributed,

24
00:01:43,370 --> 00:01:46,355
we then have to look at the logarithm of this,

25
00:01:46,355 --> 00:01:49,285
which we can use the NumPy.

26
00:01:49,285 --> 00:01:52,545
Now we see the log of these values.

27
00:01:52,545 --> 00:01:54,935
The minimum is two-and-a-half,

28
00:01:54,935 --> 00:01:58,235
whereas the maximum is almost four-and-a-half.

29
00:01:58,235 --> 00:02:01,015
These give us the limits for our bins.

30
00:02:01,015 --> 00:02:05,710
Our bin edges will be 10 to the power values between two and five,

31
00:02:05,710 --> 00:02:08,165
so that they're evenly spaced.

32
00:02:08,165 --> 00:02:10,340
Just what we have right here.

33
00:02:10,340 --> 00:02:12,995
These are now our bins.

34
00:02:12,995 --> 00:02:14,975
This plot looks a lot better.

35
00:02:14,975 --> 00:02:17,435
It shows that in a logarithmic space,

36
00:02:17,435 --> 00:02:20,465
we have almost a unimodal distribution.

37
00:02:20,465 --> 00:02:25,465
However, the tick marks are very hard to see and not quite interpretable.

38
00:02:25,465 --> 00:02:28,475
We can start by writing out the given ticks,

39
00:02:28,475 --> 00:02:31,340
but really, we just want to add a few more.

40
00:02:31,340 --> 00:02:33,695
Here's where we need to do some hardcoding.

41
00:02:33,695 --> 00:02:35,990
Because of the powers of 10,

42
00:02:35,990 --> 00:02:40,640
things aren't nice and evenly spaced as they would be normally.

43
00:02:40,640 --> 00:02:47,470
A three is about halfway between consecutive powers of 10 on a log scale.

44
00:02:47,470 --> 00:02:53,285
Adding these values to a ticks list will complete this exploratory plot.

45
00:02:53,285 --> 00:02:55,700
For example, the x ticks,

46
00:02:55,700 --> 00:02:58,640
ticks we're interested in are a 100,

47
00:02:58,640 --> 00:03:03,075
300, a 1,000 and likewise 3,000,

48
00:03:03,075 --> 00:03:04,830
and ending at 30.

49
00:03:04,830 --> 00:03:08,930
We then also, we'll create our list of

50
00:03:08,930 --> 00:03:13,510
labels by taking each of these ticks and converting them to a string.

51
00:03:13,510 --> 00:03:17,885
Then after we plot the histogram and scale the axis,

52
00:03:17,885 --> 00:03:20,125
we apply the x ticks.

53
00:03:20,125 --> 00:03:23,385
This is much easier to read.

54
00:03:23,385 --> 00:03:31,310
One thing I would like to caution you is if you add the x ticks before scaling the axis,

55
00:03:31,310 --> 00:03:32,705
they will get overwritten.

56
00:03:32,705 --> 00:03:35,160
That's a common mistake.

